04297nam a22005655i 9780226795416DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267954167 a10.7208/97802267954162doi  a(DE-B1597)523813  a(OCoLC)676695802  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPN56.3.P73bT46 2010 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a809/.9335843712a943.7121 aThomas, Alfred, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrague Palimpsest :bWriting, Memory, and the City /cAlfred Thomas. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b6 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tA Note on Translations, Quotations, and Names -- tIntroduction -- t1. Women on the Verge of History: Libuše and the Foundational Legend of Prague -- t2. Deviant Monsters and Wayward Women: The Prague Ghetto and the Legend of the Golem -- t3. The Castle Hill Was Hidden: Franz Kafka and Czech Literature -- t4. A Stranger in Prague: Writing and the Politics of Identity in Apollinaire, Nezval, and Camus -- t5. Sailing to Bohemia: Utopia, Memory, and the Holocaust in Postwar Austrian and German Writing -- tEpilogue: Postmodern Prague? -- tAppendix: Translations of Poems about Prague -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA city of immense literary mystique, Prague has inspired writers across the centuries with its beauty, cosmopolitanism, and tragic history. Envisioning the ancient city in central Europe as a multilayered text, or palimpsest, that has been constantly revised and rewritten—from the medieval and Renaissance chroniclers who legitimized the city’s foundational origins to the modernists of the early twentieth century who established its reputation as the new capital of the avant-garde—Alfred Thomas argues that Prague has become a paradoxical site of inscription and effacement, of memory and forgetting, a utopian link to the prewar and pre-Holocaust European past and a dystopia of totalitarian amnesia. Considering a wide range of writers, including the city’s most famous son, Franz Kafka, Prague Palimpsest reassesses the work of poets and novelists such as Bohumil Hrabal, Milan Kundera, Gustav Meyrink, Jan Neruda, Vítĕzslav Nezval, and Rainer Maria Rilke and engages with other famous authors who “wrote” Prague, including Guillaume Apollinaire, Ingeborg Bachmann, Albert Camus, Paul Celan, and W. G. Sebald. The result is a comparative, interdisciplinary study that helps to explain why Prague—more than any other major European city—has haunted the cultural and political imagination of the West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGolem. 0aJewish ghettoszCzech RepublicvLegends. 0aLegendszCzech RepubliczPrague. 0aLibuše (Legendary character). 0aLibuše (Legendary character). 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226795416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226795416.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles